Create my first chart!

set.seed(42)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(5000),
       aes(carat,price, col=cut)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.7, size=3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", col= "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "relationship between carat and price",
       x = "Carat",
       y = "Price USD",
       subtitle = "we found a positive relationship",
       caption = "Datasource: diamond ggpolot2"
  )

According to the correlation between carat weight and price, a higher carat weight has a greater impact on the price. Furthermore, it was discovered that the cut variety is most common between 0 and 2 carats, with the larger carats being found less frequently the higher the cut.

Chart 2 - Relationship between carat and depth

set.seed(42)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(10000), 
       aes(carat,depth, col=color))+
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", col="red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Relationship between carat and depth",
       x = "Carat",
       y = "depth",
       caption = "Datasource: diamond ggpolot2"
  )

Carat and depth comparison chart: generally low carat clustering, depth between 60 and 65, and in the colour area, clustering of less than 2 carats.

Chart 3 - Relationship between Clarity and price

set.seed(42)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(10000),
       aes(clarity, price, fill=clarity)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 4)+
  labs(title = "relationship between Clarity and Price (USD)",
       x = "Clarity",
       y = "Price",
       caption = "Datasource: diamond ggpolot2"
  )

According to the data presented in the table, sl1 clarity costs the most, whereas l1 clarity costs the least.

Chart 4 - Relationship between cut and count affect by clarity

set.seed(42)
ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, fill=clarity)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title = "relationship between Cut and Count",
       x = "cut",
       y = "count",
       caption = "Datasource: diamond ggpolot2"
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 8)

The comparison between cut and count reveals that clarity sl1 and vs2 are the highest in each cut type, whereas clarity I1 is the lowest.

Chart 5 - Relationship between carat and table affect by color

set.seed(42)
ggplot(diamonds %>% sample_n(25000),
       aes(carat,table, col=color)) + 
  geom_point(alpha=0.5, size=2) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", col="red") + 
  theme_minimal() +
  facet_wrap(~ cut, ncol=3)+
  labs(title = "relationship between Cut and Count",
       x = "Carat",
       y = "Table",
       caption = "Datasource: diamond ggpolot2"
  ) +
   scale_color_brewer(type = "qual", palette = 7)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The comparison graph between carat and table revealed that they are clustered at carat not exceeding 2 and finding table between 50 and 70, whereas the higher cut type will find table not exceeding 65.
